<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911001-0046</DOCNO><DOCID>911001-0046.</DOCID><HL>   System Industries Inc. Role</HL><DATE>10/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   BA SYI</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>DEFENSE CONTRACTS (DFC)</NS><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   MILPITAS, Calif. -- System Industries Inc. said its roleas subcontractor to Boeing Co. as part of Boeing's $1.6billion contract with the Army will bring System $160 millionin revenue over three years.   System, a maker of computer-datastorage equipment, said itwill sell disk and tape drives valued at $160 million toBoeing as part of the aerospace concern's contract, awardedyesterday, to provide the Army with a huge computer system.</LP><TEXT>   The subcontracting deal is a bonanza for System, which hashad net losses in eight of the past 12 quarters. &quot;This is abig revenue uplift for the company,&quot; said Jesse Bean,System's treasurer. &quot;It's very good news for us given wherewe've been.&quot;   Mr. Bean said the sales would be spread out over threeyears, with 10% of the revenue coming in the year ending July1992, 60% in fiscal 1993, and 30% in fiscal 1994.   In American Stock Exchange trading yesterday, Systemclosed at $3, up $1.   System had net income in the fourth quarter ended July 27of $46,000, or one cent a share, on revenue of $22.9 million.System has blamed its recent troubles on a soft but highlycompetitive market, the Gulf War and the recession.   (See related story: Boeing Receives Army Contract ForComputers --- Eleven-Year Pact Is Valued At $1.6 Billion andBeats Rival Computer Sciences&quot; -- WSJ Oct. 1, 1991)</TEXT></DOC>